Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: The core challenge in long-tailed visual recognition lies in the severe under-representation of tail classes, which leads to poor feature generalization and biased decision boundaries. While self-distillation has shown promise in transferring knowledge from head to tail classes, most existing methods operate at either the image or patch level without sufficient semantic guidance—resulting in the transfer of irrelevant or noisy patterns. Inspired by Paper 1’s use of patch-level self-distillation and decoupled learning, Paper 2’s emphasis on distributional semantics for richer supervision signals, and Paper 3’s structured reasoning through semantic-visual interaction, I propose a novel framework that introduces *semantic governance* into patch-level self-distillation. Unlike prior work that treats all patches equally during knowledge transfer, my idea leverages learned semantic prototypes to guide which patch-level patterns should be distilled and how they should influence tail class representations. This ensures that only semantically coherent and discriminative visual motifs—shared across head and tail classes—are transferred, avoiding the propagation of spurious correlations. Furthermore, by integrating a prototype-based contrastive mechanism with semantic consistency constraints, the model learns more robust and balanced representations. This approach fundamentally differs from standard self-distillation or supervised contrastive learning by introducing a *semantic gate* that modulates knowledge flow based on class-invariant structural patterns, enabling more effective long-tailed recognition.

