{
  "Idea": "The proposed idea, 'Semantically-Governed Patch-Level Self-Distillation for Long-Tailed Visual Recognition', addresses the critical issue of representation imbalance in long-tailed datasets by introducing a novel self-distillation framework that selectively transfers patch-level visual patterns from head to tail classes under explicit semantic control. In traditional self-distillation methods, features from well-learned head classes are used as soft targets for less-represented tail classes, but this often results in suboptimal transfer due to semantic misalignment—i.e., transferring texture-heavy or background-specific patches that do not generalize meaningfully. Our method overcomes this limitation by first constructing class-agnostic semantic prototypes via a learnable memory bank that captures shared visual concepts (e.g., 'wing', 'wheel', 'handle') across categories. These prototypes are updated dynamically using moving average encoding and serve as semantic anchors. During training, each image is decomposed into local patches, and their features are matched against these prototypes to compute a semantic relevance score. Only those patches with high alignment to stable, cross-class semantic concepts are selected for distillation. A dual-path architecture then enables knowledge transfer: one branch processes original images with standard classification loss, while the other uses augmented views and enforces patch-level consistency via a prototype-guided distillation loss. Crucially, we introduce a Semantic Gating Mechanism (SGM) that modulates the distillation weight per patch based on its prototype coherence, ensuring that only semantically meaningful and transferable patterns contribute to tail class learning. Additionally, we employ a decoupled contrastive objective similar to Paper 1 but extended to patch-prototype space, encouraging intra-prototype compactness while separating inter-prototype clusters. This combination allows the model to learn disentangled, generalizable features even with few samples. The significance of this work lies in bridging low-level visual patterns with high-level semantics in a self-supervised manner, enabling more intelligent and context-aware knowledge transfer. It offers a paradigm shift from blind feature copying to semantically informed distillation, potentially improving performance across various long-tailed vision tasks such as fine-grained classification, medical imaging, and autonomous driving perception systems.",
