ystem adapts over time: as tail class representations stabilize, the router reduces reliance on head-class inputs, preventing overfitting to dominant patterns. This creates a self-regulating distillation loop that evolves with model confidence. The significance of this work lies in transforming knowledge transfer from a passive copying mechanism into an active, interpretable reasoning process. It offers a new lens on long-tailed learning—one where models learn not just *what* to transfer, but *whether* and *why* to transfer—enabling more robust generalization in data-scarce regimes. Applications span medical imaging (rare disease detection), wildlife monitoring, and autonomous systems operating in open-world environments.",
